          "body": "The chapter's second strophe (12:4-6) has an unmistakably missiological shape. Four imperatives press outward in verse 4: give thanks, call on His name, make His deeds known among the peoples, cause them to remember that His name is exalted. The scope is explicit — *among the peoples* (*ammim*), the nations of the earth. Verse 5 widens it further: 'let this be known throughout the earth.' Isaiah 12 is not a private devotional hymn; it is a missionary commission embedded in a doxology. The redeemed community is responsible not only for its own worship but for ensuring that the nations hear what God has done. D. A. Carson, commenting on the missionary trajectory of the Psalms and prophets, notes that doxology and mission are inseparable in the Old Testament — Israel was never saved for her own sake alone but to be a kingdom of priests mediating God's presence to the nations (Exodus 19:6). Isaiah 12 is the precise fulfillment of that calling: having drawn from the springs of salvation, the community now announces the Source of those springs to everyone who has not yet drawn."
